    <article xml:id="notes">
        <section xml:id="sec-Galois-extensions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Galois field extensions</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We begin with the following example to illustrate the <sq>Fundamental Theorem of Galois Theory</sq>.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <lemma xml:id="lem-splitting-field-of-third-root-of-2">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>\omega\in\C</m> denotes a primitive third root of unity, and that <m>\alpha=\sqrt[3]{2}\in\R</m> denotes the real third root of <m>2</m>. Let <m>K=\Q\left(\alpha,\omega\right)</m> be a field generated over <m>\Q</m> by <m>\alpha,\omega</m>. Then,
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>K/\Q</m> is Galois field extension, and
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>[K:\Q]=6</m> and <m>\{1,\alpha,\alpha^2,\omega,\omega\alpha,\omega\alpha^2\}</m> is a <m>\Q</m>-basis of <m>K/\Q</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The field <m>K</m> is the splitting field of an irreducible separable polynomial <m>x^3-2</m> over <m>\Q</m> (see <xref ref="ex-degree-of-field-extension"/>). Therefore, <m>K/\Q</m> Galois.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        This follows from <xref ref="ex-degree-of-field-extension"/> and the observation that <m>\alpha^2\beta=\omega</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </proof>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-Galois-group-of-splitting-field-of-third-root-of-2">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Keep notations of <xref ref="lem-splitting-field-of-third-root-of-2"/>. The Galois group of <m>K/\Q</m> is isomorphic to the permutation group <m>S_3</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We consider <m>\{1,\alpha,\alpha^2,\omega,\omega\alpha,\omega\alpha^2\}</m> as a basis of <m>K/\Q</m>. Define the following automorphisms.
            <me>
                \sigma\colon\
                \begin{array}{1}\alpha\mapsto\omega\alpha\\\omega\mapsto\omega\end{array}
                \quad\text{and}\quad
                \tau\colon\
                \begin{array}{1}\alpha\mapsto\alpha\\\omega\mapsto\omega^2\end{array}
            </me>
            One checks that <m>\sigma^3=\unit_K=\tau^2</m> and that <m>\tau\circ\sigma\circ\tau=\sigma^{-1}=\sigma^2</m>. Furthermore, as <m>K/\Q</m> is a Galois field extension of degree <m>6</m>, the Galois group is
            <me>
                \{e,\sigma,\sigma^2,\tau,\tau\sigma,\tau\sigma^2\}\simeq S_3.
            </me>
            
        </p>
    </proof>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-subgroups-of-splitting-field-of-third-root-of-2">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Keep notations of <xref ref="lem-splitting-field-of-third-root-of-2"/>. Following are all the subfields of <m>K/\Q</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We use the fundamental theorem of Galois theory. Note that following are all the subgroups of <m>S_3</m>.
            <me>
                H_0=\{e\}, H_1=\{e,\sigma,\sigma^2\}, H_2=\{e,\tau\}, H_3=\{e,\tau\sigma\}, H_4=\{e,\tau\sigma^2\}, \text{ and }, H_5=S_3
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            We calculate the fixed of of <m>H_1</m>.
        </p>
    </proof>
